Thick target correction was made
Four 60% HPGe detectors placed an average of
about 12 cm from the target were used for detection
of scattered gamma rays. The detectors were placed at
a scattering angle of 120deg, with two detectors in
the horizontal plane, and two in the vertical plane.
They were shielded with 2.5 cm Pb on all sides, and
Pb (0.55 cm) and Cu (0.4 cm) filters were placed in
front of the detectors to reduce the intensity of low
energy photons hitting the detector.
Statistical uncertainty
Experiment performed using the
quasimonoenergetic gamma-ray beam at the HIgS
facility, Triangle Universities Nuclear Laboratory,
Durham.
Quasimonoenergetic gamma rays are produced by
Compton backscattering of photons from free electron
laser (FEL) on electrons in electron storage ring. In
no-loss mode FEL wavelength can be varied from 350 nm
to 1064 nm and electron energy from 230 MeV to 750
MeV, resulting in gamma rays in energy range 1-30 MeV
The average resonance properties were measured using
transmission nuclear resonance fluorescence (NRF)
method. In contrast with direct NRF, where measured
gamma rays are gamma-rays directly emitted from the
decay of states excited in measured nuclei, the
transmission method measures the development of notches
following transmission through measured material. The
absorber is placed upstream of the scattering target.
The average resonance properties were determined from
the ratio of measurement with and without absorber.
In the present experiment the scattering target was
natural metallic Ta target 0.74 cm thick. At 2.28 Mev
two absorption targets were used a Ta absorber 2 cm
thick and Pb absorber 2.6 cm thick. At the energy of
2.75 MeV the data set was obtained from the ratio of
a Ta absorber (3 cm) to no absorber. All sources of
background were subtracted separately  - pileup of
counts, room background, small-angle Compton
scattering and coherent scattering
Natural metallic Ta targets
were used; the scattering target was 0.74 cm thick.
